What?

  • unsupervised data mining technique
  • employed by retailers to understand purchase behaviors
  • used to determine what items are frequently bought together
  • it creates IF-THEN scenario rules

Why ?

  • store layout
  • online recommendation engines
  • targeted marketing campaigns
  • cross-selling
  • up-selling
  • catalogue design
  • enhance customer experience

Advantages

  • cost-effective
  • insightful
  • flexible
  • actionable

Use Cases

  • retail
  • telecommunications
  • banks
  • insurance
  • medical
  • manufacturing

Steps

  • frequent itemset generation
  • rules generation

  • unit price
  • customer id
  • country

Generate Rules

rules <- apriori(basket_data, parameter = list(supp=0.009, conf=0.8, 
    target = "rules", maxlen = 4))

Number of Rules

Redundant Rules

rules_redundant <-
  basket_rules %>%
  is.subset(rules) %>%
  colSums() %>%
  is_greater_than(1) %>%
  which()

What influenced purchase of product X?

sugar_rules <- apriori(basket_data, parameter = list(supp = 0.009, conf = 0.8),

Summary

WHAT

unsupervised data mining technique employed by retailers to understand purchase behaviors and used to determine what items are frequently bought together

WHY

store layout, online recommendation engines, targeted marketing campaigns, cross-selling, up-selling, catalogue design, enhance customer experience etc

ADVANTAGES

cost-effective, insightful, flexible and actionable

USAGE

retail, telecommunications, banks, insurance, medical, manufacturing

WARNING

  • directionality of rule is lost while using lift
  • confidence as a measure can be misleading
